Docs: Compare returns an integer comparing two byte slices lexicographically.
The result will be 0 if a==b, -1 if a < b, and +1 if a > b.
A nil argument is equivalent to an empty slice.
Funcs.Name: Compare

Docs: Contains reports whether subslice is within b.
Funcs.Name: Contains

Docs: ContainsAny reports whether any of the UTF-8-encoded code points in chars are within b.
Funcs.Name: ContainsAny

Docs: ContainsRune reports whether the rune is contained in the UTF-8-encoded byte slice b.
Funcs.Name: ContainsRune

Docs: Count counts the number of non-overlapping instances of sep in s.
If sep is an empty slice, Count returns 1 + the number of UTF-8-encoded code points in s.
Funcs.Name: Count

Docs: Equal reports whether a and b
are the same length and contain the same bytes.
A nil argument is equivalent to an empty slice.
Funcs.Name: Equal

Docs: EqualFold reports whether s and t, interpreted as UTF-8 strings,
are equal under Unicode case-folding, which is a more general
form of case-insensitivity.
Funcs.Name: EqualFold

Docs: Fields interprets s as a sequence of UTF-8-encoded code points.
It splits the slice s around each instance of one or more consecutive white space
characters, as defined by unicode.IsSpace, returning a slice of subslices of s or an
empty slice if s contains only white space.
Funcs.Name: Fields

Docs: FieldsFunc interprets s as a sequence of UTF-8-encoded code points.
It splits the slice s at each run of code points c satisfying f(c) and
returns a slice of subslices of s. If all code points in s satisfy f(c), or
len(s) == 0, an empty slice is returned.
FieldsFunc makes no guarantees about the order in which it calls f(c).
If f does not return consistent results for a given c, FieldsFunc may crash.
Funcs.Name: FieldsFunc

Docs: HasPrefix tests whether the byte slice s begins with prefix.
Funcs.Name: HasPrefix

Docs: HasSuffix tests whether the byte slice s ends with suffix.
Funcs.Name: HasSuffix

Docs: Index returns the index of the first instance of sep in s, or -1 if sep is not present in s.
Funcs.Name: Index

Docs: IndexAny interprets s as a sequence of UTF-8-encoded Unicode code points.
It returns the byte index of the first occurrence in s of any of the Unicode
code points in chars. It returns -1 if chars is empty or if there is no code
point in common.
Funcs.Name: IndexAny

Docs: IndexByte returns the index of the first instance of c in b, or -1 if c is not present in b.
Funcs.Name: IndexByte

Funcs.Signature: func IndexFunc(s []byte, f func(r rune) bool) int
Docs: IndexFunc interprets s as a sequence of UTF-8-encoded code points.
It returns the byte index in s of the first Unicode
code point satisfying f(c), or -1 if none do.
Funcs.Name: IndexFunc

Docs: IndexRune interprets s as a sequence of UTF-8-encoded code points.
It returns the byte index of the first occurrence in s of the given rune.
It returns -1 if rune is not present in s.
If r is utf8.RuneError, it returns the first instance of any
invalid UTF-8 byte sequence.
Funcs.Name: IndexRune

Docs: Join concatenates the elements of s to create a new byte slice. The separator
sep is placed between elements in the resulting slice.
Funcs.Name: Join

Docs: LastIndex returns the index of the last instance of sep in s, or -1 if sep is not present in s.
Funcs.Name: LastIndex

Docs: LastIndexAny interprets s as a sequence of UTF-8-encoded Unicode code
points. It returns the byte index of the last occurrence in s of any of
the Unicode code points in chars. It returns -1 if chars is empty or if
there is no code point in common.
Funcs.Name: LastIndexAny

Docs: LastIndexByte returns the index of the last instance of c in s, or -1 if c is not present in s.
Funcs.Name: LastIndexByte

Funcs.Signature: func LastIndexFunc(s []byte, f func(r rune) bool) int
Docs: LastIndexFunc interprets s as a sequence of UTF-8-encoded code points.
It returns the byte index in s of the last Unicode
code point satisfying f(c), or -1 if none do.
Funcs.Name: LastIndexFunc

Funcs.Signature: func Map(mapping func(r rune) rune, s []byte) []byte
Docs: Map returns a copy of the byte slice s with all its characters modified
according to the mapping function. If mapping returns a negative value, the character is
dropped from the byte slice with no replacement. The characters in s and the
output are interpreted as UTF-8-encoded code points.
Funcs.Name: Map

Docs: NewBuffer creates and initializes a new Buffer using buf as its
initial contents. The new Buffer takes ownership of buf, and the
caller should not use buf after this call. NewBuffer is intended to
prepare a Buffer to read existing data. It can also be used to set
the initial size of the internal buffer for writing. To do that,
buf should have the desired capacity but a length of zero.
In most cases, new(Buffer) (or just declaring a Buffer variable) is
sufficient to initialize a Buffer.
Funcs.Name: NewBuffer

Docs: NewBufferString creates and initializes a new Buffer using string s as its
initial contents. It is intended to prepare a buffer to read an existing
string.
In most cases, new(Buffer) (or just declaring a Buffer variable) is
sufficient to initialize a Buffer.
Funcs.Name: NewBufferString

Docs: NewReader returns a new Reader reading from b.
Funcs.Name: NewReader

Docs: Repeat returns a new byte slice consisting of count copies of b.
It panics if count is negative or if
the result of (len(b) * count) overflows.
Funcs.Name: Repeat

Funcs.Signature: func Replace(s []byte, old []byte, new []byte, n int) []byte
Docs: Replace returns a copy of the slice s with the first n
non-overlapping instances of old replaced by new.
If old is empty, it matches at the beginning of the slice
and after each UTF-8 sequence, yielding up to k+1 replacements
for a k-rune slice.
If n < 0, there is no limit on the number of replacements.
Funcs.Name: Replace

Docs: ReplaceAll returns a copy of the slice s with all
non-overlapping instances of old replaced by new.
If old is empty, it matches at the beginning of the slice
and after each UTF-8 sequence, yielding up to k+1 replacements
for a k-rune slice.
Funcs.Name: ReplaceAll

Docs: Runes interprets s as a sequence of UTF-8-encoded code points.
It returns a slice of runes (Unicode code points) equivalent to s.
Funcs.Name: Runes

Docs: Split slices s into all subslices separated by sep and returns a slice of
the subslices between those separators.
If sep is empty, Split splits after each UTF-8 sequence.
It is equivalent to SplitN with a count of -1.
Funcs.Name: Split

Docs: SplitAfter slices s into all subslices after each instance of sep and
returns a slice of those subslices.
If sep is empty, SplitAfter splits after each UTF-8 sequence.
It is equivalent to SplitAfterN with a count of -1.
Funcs.Name: SplitAfter

Docs: SplitAfterN slices s into subslices after each instance of sep and
returns a slice of those subslices.
If sep is empty, SplitAfterN splits after each UTF-8 sequence.
The count determines the number of subslices to return:
n > 0: at most n subslices; the last subslice will be the unsplit remainder.
n == 0: the result is nil (zero subslices)
n < 0: all subslices
Funcs.Name: SplitAfterN

Docs: SplitN slices s into subslices separated by sep and returns a slice of
the subslices between those separators.
If sep is empty, SplitN splits after each UTF-8 sequence.
The count determines the number of subslices to return:
n > 0: at most n subslices; the last subslice will be the unsplit remainder.
n == 0: the result is nil (zero subslices)
n < 0: all subslices
Funcs.Name: SplitN

Docs: Title treats s as UTF-8-encoded bytes and returns a copy with all Unicode letters that begin
words mapped to their title case.
BUG(rsc): The rule Title uses for word boundaries does not handle Unicode punctuation properly.
Funcs.Name: Title

Docs: ToLower returns a copy of the byte slice s with all Unicode letters mapped to
their lower case.
Funcs.Name: ToLower

Docs: ToLowerSpecial treats s as UTF-8-encoded bytes and returns a copy with all the Unicode letters mapped to their
lower case, giving priority to the special casing rules.
Funcs.Name: ToLowerSpecial

Docs: ToTitle treats s as UTF-8-encoded bytes and returns a copy with all the Unicode letters mapped to their title case.
Funcs.Name: ToTitle

Docs: ToTitleSpecial treats s as UTF-8-encoded bytes and returns a copy with all the Unicode letters mapped to their
title case, giving priority to the special casing rules.
Funcs.Name: ToTitleSpecial

Docs: ToUpper returns a copy of the byte slice s with all Unicode letters mapped to
their upper case.
Funcs.Name: ToUpper

Docs: ToUpperSpecial treats s as UTF-8-encoded bytes and returns a copy with all the Unicode letters mapped to their
upper case, giving priority to the special casing rules.
Funcs.Name: ToUpperSpecial

Docs: ToValidUTF8 treats s as UTF-8-encoded bytes and returns a copy with each run of bytes
representing invalid UTF-8 replaced with the bytes in replacement, which may be empty.
Funcs.Name: ToValidUTF8

Docs: Trim returns a subslice of s by slicing off all leading and
trailing UTF-8-encoded code points contained in cutset.
Funcs.Name: Trim

Funcs.Signature: func TrimFunc(s []byte, f func(r rune) bool) []byte
Docs: TrimFunc returns a subslice of s by slicing off all leading and trailing
UTF-8-encoded code points c that satisfy f(c).
Funcs.Name: TrimFunc

Docs: TrimLeft returns a subslice of s by slicing off all leading
UTF-8-encoded code points contained in cutset.
Funcs.Name: TrimLeft

Funcs.Signature: func TrimLeftFunc(s []byte, f func(r rune) bool) []byte
Docs: TrimLeftFunc treats s as UTF-8-encoded bytes and returns a subslice of s by slicing off
all leading UTF-8-encoded code points c that satisfy f(c).
Funcs.Name: TrimLeftFunc

Docs: TrimPrefix returns s without the provided leading prefix string.
If s doesn't start with prefix, s is returned unchanged.
Funcs.Name: TrimPrefix

Docs: TrimRight returns a subslice of s by slicing off all trailing
UTF-8-encoded code points that are contained in cutset.
Funcs.Name: TrimRight

Funcs.Signature: func TrimRightFunc(s []byte, f func(r rune) bool) []byte
Docs: TrimRightFunc returns a subslice of s by slicing off all trailing
UTF-8-encoded code points c that satisfy f(c).
Funcs.Name: TrimRightFunc

Docs: TrimSpace returns a subslice of s by slicing off all leading and
trailing white space, as defined by Unicode.
Funcs.Name: TrimSpace

Docs: TrimSuffix returns s without the provided trailing suffix string.
If s doesn't end with suffix, s is returned unchanged.
Funcs.Name: TrimSuffix

Docs: Bytes returns a slice of length b.Len() holding the unread portion of the buffer.
The slice is valid for use only until the next buffer modification (that is,
only until the next call to a method like Read, Write, Reset, or Truncate).
The slice aliases the buffer content at least until the next buffer modification,
so immediate changes to the slice will affect the result of future reads.
Bytes returns a slice of length b.Len() holding the unread portion of the buffer.
The slice is valid for use only until the next buffer modification (that is,
only until the next call to a method like Read, Write, Reset, or Truncate).
The slice aliases the buffer content at least until the next buffer modification,
so immediate changes to the slice will affect the result of future reads.
Func.Name: Bytes

Docs: Cap returns the capacity of the buffer's underlying byte slice, that is, the
total space allocated for the buffer's data.
Cap returns the capacity of the buffer's underlying byte slice, that is, the
total space allocated for the buffer's data.
Func.Name: Cap

Docs: Grow grows the buffer's capacity, if necessary, to guarantee space for
another n bytes. After Grow(n), at least n bytes can be written to the
buffer without another allocation.
If n is negative, Grow will panic.
If the buffer can't grow it will panic with ErrTooLarge.
Grow grows the buffer's capacity, if necessary, to guarantee space for
another n bytes. After Grow(n), at least n bytes can be written to the
buffer without another allocation.
If n is negative, Grow will panic.
If the buffer can't grow it will panic with ErrTooLarge.
Func.Name: Grow

Docs: Len returns the number of bytes of the unread portion of the buffer;
b.Len() == len(b.Bytes()).
Len returns the number of bytes of the unread portion of the buffer;
b.Len() == len(b.Bytes()).
Func.Name: Len

Docs: Next returns a slice containing the next n bytes from the buffer,
advancing the buffer as if the bytes had been returned by Read.
If there are fewer than n bytes in the buffer, Next returns the entire buffer.
The slice is only valid until the next call to a read or write method.
Next returns a slice containing the next n bytes from the buffer,
advancing the buffer as if the bytes had been returned by Read.
If there are fewer than n bytes in the buffer, Next returns the entire buffer.
The slice is only valid until the next call to a read or write method.
Func.Name: Next

Docs: Read reads the next len(p) bytes from the buffer or until the buffer
is drained. The return value n is the number of bytes read. If the
buffer has no data to return, err is io.EOF (unless len(p) is zero);
otherwise it is nil.
Read reads the next len(p) bytes from the buffer or until the buffer
is drained. The return value n is the number of bytes read. If the
buffer has no data to return, err is io.EOF (unless len(p) is zero);
otherwise it is nil.
Func.Name: Read

Docs: ReadByte reads and returns the next byte from the buffer.
If no byte is available, it returns error io.EOF.
ReadByte reads and returns the next byte from the buffer.
If no byte is available, it returns error io.EOF.
Func.Name: ReadByte

Docs: ReadBytes reads until the first occurrence of delim in the input,
returning a slice containing the data up to and including the delimiter.
If ReadBytes encounters an error before finding a delimiter,
it returns the data read before the error and the error itself (often io.EOF).
ReadBytes returns err != nil if and only if the returned data does not end in
delim.
ReadBytes reads until the first occurrence of delim in the input,

If ReadBytes encounters an error before finding a delimiter,
it returns the data read before the error and the error itself (often io.EOF).
ReadBytes returns err != nil if and only if the returned data does not end in
delim.
Func.Name: ReadBytes

Docs: ReadFrom reads data from r until EOF and appends it to the buffer, growing
the buffer as needed. The return value n is the number of bytes read. Any
error except io.EOF encountered during the read is also returned. If the
buffer becomes too large, ReadFrom will panic with ErrTooLarge.
ReadFrom reads data from r until EOF and appends it to the buffer, growing

Docs: ReadRune reads and returns the next UTF-8-encoded
Unicode code point from the buffer.
If no bytes are available, the error returned is io.EOF.
If the bytes are an erroneous UTF-8 encoding, it
consumes one byte and returns U+FFFD, 1.

Func.Signature: func (*Buffer).ReadRune() (r rune, size int, err error)
Docs: ReadRune reads and returns the next UTF-8-encoded
Unicode code point from the buffer.
If no bytes are available, the error returned is io.EOF.
If the bytes are an erroneous UTF-8 encoding, it
consumes one byte and returns U+FFFD, 1.
Func.Name: ReadRune

Docs: ReadString reads until the first occurrence of delim in the input,
returning a string containing the data up to and including the delimiter.
If ReadString encounters an error before finding a delimiter,
it returns the data read before the error and the error itself (often io.EOF).
ReadString returns err != nil if and only if the returned data does not end
in delim.

Docs: Reset resets the buffer to be empty,
but it retains the underlying storage for use by future writes.
Reset is the same as Truncate(0).
Reset resets the buffer to be empty,
but it retains the underlying storage for use by future writes.
Reset is the same as Truncate(0).
Func.Name: Reset

Docs: String returns the contents of the unread portion of the buffer
as a string. If the Buffer is a nil pointer, it returns "<nil>".
To build strings more efficiently, see the strings.Builder type.
String returns the contents of the unread portion of the buffer
as a string. If the Buffer is a nil pointer, it returns "<nil>".
To build strings more efficiently, see the strings.Builder type.
Func.Name: String

Docs: Truncate discards all but the first n unread bytes from the buffer
but continues to use the same allocated storage.
It panics if n is negative or greater than the length of the buffer.
Truncate discards all but the first n unread bytes from the buffer
but continues to use the same allocated storage.
It panics if n is negative or greater than the length of the buffer.
Func.Name: Truncate

Docs: UnreadByte unreads the last byte returned by the most recent successful
read operation that read at least one byte. If a write has happened since
the last read, if the last read returned an error, or if the read read zero
bytes, UnreadByte returns an error.
UnreadByte unreads the last byte returned by the most recent successful
read operation that read at least one byte. If a write has happened since
the last read, if the last read returned an error, or if the read read zero
bytes, UnreadByte returns an error.
Func.Name: UnreadByte

Docs: UnreadRune unreads the last rune returned by ReadRune.
If the most recent read or write operation on the buffer was
not a successful ReadRune, UnreadRune returns an error.  (In this regard
it is stricter than UnreadByte, which will unread the last byte
from any read operation.)
UnreadRune unreads the last rune returned by ReadRune.

Docs: Write appends the contents of p to the buffer, growing the buffer as
needed. The return value n is the length of p; err is always nil. If the
buffer becomes too large, Write will panic with ErrTooLarge.

Docs: WriteByte appends the byte c to the buffer, growing the buffer as needed.
The returned error is always nil, but is included to match bufio.Writer's
WriteByte. If the buffer becomes too large, WriteByte will panic with
ErrTooLarge.

buffer, returning its length and an error, which is always nil but is

if it becomes too large, WriteRune will panic with ErrTooLarge.

Docs: WriteString appends the contents of s to the buffer, growing the buffer as
needed. The return value n is the length of s; err is always nil. If the
buffer becomes too large, WriteString will panic with ErrTooLarge.

The return value n is the number of bytes written; it always fits into an
int, but it is int64 to match the io.WriterTo interface. Any error
encountered during the write is also returned.
